description.text:
This is an ice scraper made to attach to the popular Snow Brūm snow removal tool: https://amzn.com/B0007LDXLA

Its biggest weakness, however, is that it doesn't have a scraper attached like many removal tools - which means you need to go out and buy something separate (which is annoying).

This scraper is designed to fit snuggly over the end of the telescoping pole's handle and accommodate the special triangular-holed cap. You will need 3 zip ties to keep it permanently attached during use.

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

Mini

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.25

Infill:

20%

Notes:

The scraper pictured was printed at .4mm with a .5mm nozzle to speed up the print and verify all dimensions fit. It also has a particularly low infill (hence the small gaps seen on the top).

I would want to print with a smaller layer height (.25-.3mm) so that the scraper's bevel looks a bit nicer with a less stepped appearance due to the large layer height used. This is largely an aesthetic choice, however.
This was designed with Fusion 360 and sliced with Cura (Lulzbot edition).

Special note about filament type

If you plan to print this and leave it in your car, please keep in mind that PLA can easily warp or melt at the temps that can be reached in a confined automobile. While this isn't as big of an issue during the colder months when you're likely to use this scraper, consider where you will store it during the off season.

I printed mine with Colorfabb nGen, which I've noticed holds up much better in heat than PLA. ABS would be another viable option as well.

description.text:
I needed some hooks to hang some pot holders and came up with these. We have vintage metal cabinets so I integrated a magnet into the design, but you could simply use double sided tape or some other adhesive as a fastener. I put up three styles, but I think they are all pretty much functionally identical.

I designed these for easy printing with no need for support material. The hook or peg is printed along the x or y axis (depending how you orient them on your print bed) which is the most structurally sound orientation for printing. They sure seem pretty strong for what they are and hold our pot holders with no problems.

I installed small rare earth magnets in these. They are round, 8mm wide by 3mm tall (0.315" x 0.118"). I got mine at Micro Center, but any magnets of that size will work (and they hold on to our cabinets really well) or you can modify the .stl for a different size. This project is dedicated to building a set of simplest bread boards to show principles of reading world data in different environments.   
The resulting set of bread boards could be useful for those who want to study and understand how sofisticated sensor systems work through learning the simplest design possible. Boards' eagle files included in the project could also be used to start a more advanced sensor solution project by simple adding/editing components.  
Each sensor board is represented with an Eagle schematic and board file, those are supplied with essential datasheets. To test sensor readings each board has an integrated RS-232 communication port. Basic C/python programs are provided to test the sensor in real environment via computer visualisation/interaction.  
The project was inspired by Neil Gershenfeld's work, his class in Fab Academy and still has code written by him.  
Provided design files are for Eagle CAD V6.5.

This is my first design with moving parts, a fully customziable simple escalator. When leaving out the steps it can also be used as a conveyor belt or maybe tank tracks without the chassis.

Before printing everything it is best to print a couple chain links to see if they work. When using multiple links per step the chain link with the socket on top can be used to connect both the horizontal and vertical parts of one step, the link without the socket can be used in between. The pulley should be big enough that the chain with the mounted steps can bend around it, so it is best to print one of the pulleys next to try that out. The pulleys with the mounted chain are placed on the axes in a way that the hole in the chassis aligns with the square hole of one of the pulleys. Make sure the pulleys rotate easily. You will need 6 pins to assemble the chassis and mount the handle. Inserting the pins can be quite tough, I did it carefully with a hammer. When the chassis is assembled the crank can be joined with the handle and mounted trough the hole of the chassis with a pin.

title: i3 X Axis Linear Rail System

description.text:
While usable, this is still a WIP

I designed this to replace the 8mm smooth roads on my Hesine m505 with 400mm MGN12 linear rails and 10mm wide belts. This design incorporates a floating X axis idler to help reduce Z wobble artifacts. Currently it is using an old fan duct design and it is also compatible with my Z endstop adjuster.
I will later update this for use with 450mm rails (what I should have ordered), and different pulley sizes.
Note that this is for printers with a spacing of 22mm between lead screw and smooth rod centres.

LM10 version now availiable.
2016/11/15 Now with even more overkill. SFU12 ballscrews and LM10 smooth roads.

BOM;
mk8 extruder idler, spring and supplied M3 bolts.
2x 400mm MGN 12 linear rails and 2x H (long) blocks.
16/20T 5mm bore G2T gear and idler pulley
1X M5x20 bolt + nut
An assortment of M3x 5/10/15/20 TBD + nuts
1X M3x40mm
Small piece of PTFE tube

i3

Doesn't Matter

Notes:

I used 2 perimeters/shell with 3 bottom 4 top layers. Feel free to use more for added strength/stiffness.
All parts are oriented for best results, some will require supports.

Ensure that you have excellent layer bonding and that the rails fit nicely. There is a small built in tolerance but warping or poor overhang performance will cause the opening to be too small and inserting the rails will split the part.

You may need to drill out the 3mm (3.3 design) holes and tap the 2.5s if they come out undersized.

description.text:
I made a few modifications to simonkuehling's x carriage so that it would fit on my MendelMax better.  These modifications include: shifting the belt clamps over so the belts are in a straight line with the pulley and moving the belt clamps farther apart so that the belt can be tensioned more easily.  I also used the beefier (3mm thick) version of jonaskuehling's LM8UU clamps, and added a tab with holes in it to mount a printed opto-flag.
I've tried to keep it as parametric as possible.  There is a boolean for the opto flag in the scad file, so just change it from 1 to 0 if you don't want that tab on there.

title: Seatpost mount for Cateye Reflex light on Giant TCR/Defy aero seatpost

description.text:
I ride bikes, and am of the opinion that you should always have a blinky taillight for visibility when riding on the road. Only problem is I'm forgetful and often fail to turn on my taillight, which kinda defeats the purpose. Because of this, I love the Cateye Reflex taillight ( (https://smile.amazon.com/gp/product/B003WCFJZE/) ) which turns on automatically when you move the bike. (although you do have to tape over the light sensor which normally makes it blink only at night - but that's very easy and covered in my review on the Amazon page)

The big problem with the Cateye taillight is that it comes with two different clamps, and they're both for round seatposts. For most bikes on the market, this isn't a problem, but I have a Giant Defy, which has an aero teardrop-shaped seatpost. Thus, I wasn't able to use the taillight on that bike. However, once a good friend got me interested in 3D printing again, this was one of the first problems I thought I could solve. Even before I had a 3D printer, I had drawn up the design, and am thrilled to say that the first iteration might not be beautiful, but it actually works! I've got several other designs which are several iterations in and still not 100% where they need to be.

This will be a very niche item - only folks with the Giant Defy or TCR with the aero seatpost - but if you're out there, I think you will be REALLY happy to have this option. Transfer the 8mm nut from one of the seat clamps.

For this thing, PLA is recommended caused by it's higher rigidity.

First version was for an H made of 50mm x 4mm profile cause the online catalog said that a local market has exactly that stuff, but the catalog was faulty and all I could find was 50mm x 3mm. This is an experiment in OpenForge supporting the OpenLOCK system completely. We've been in discussions with Printable Scenery and we heartily support this open standard for locking tiles.

When using an external wall based system, there are many ways to tessellate. With the standard OpenForge External tiles, I designed them to do it entirely with the walls. Long ago, I took the other path of using what I called wall buffers. OpenLOCK does both. This set is a series of half floors with the same table area as the walls.

For instructions on how to get started with OpenForge, take a look at our tutorials.
